<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1440,713,2033]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
Note: 
<bibRefCitation author="Vari" box="[269,401,1289,1313]" firstAuthor="Vari" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref201509" refString="Vari, L. (1961) South African Lepidoptera. Vol. I. Lithocolletidae. Transvaal Museum Memoir, 12, 238 pp. 112 pls." type="book" year="1961">Vári (1961)</bibRefCitation>
frequently used the term &quot;metallotype&quot; to indicate the first specimen of the opposite sex to the holotype, but which was not included in the original type series, in order to distinguish it from the allotype. That term was introduced by 
<bibRefCitation author="Munro" box="[503,667,1361,1385]" firstAuthor="Munro" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="15" refId="ref198204" refString="Munro, H. K. (1957) Sphenella and some allied genera (Trypetidae, Diptera). Journal of the entomological Society of South Africa, 20, 15." type="journal article" year="1957">Munro (1957)</bibRefCitation>
, but it is not recognized by the International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. We retain it anyway in quoting the labels as it gives extra information.
</paragraph>
